04836nam a22008655i 9780812290165DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20141999pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013937042  a97808122901657 a10.9783/97808122901652doi  a(DE-B1597)449271  a(OCoLC)922696003  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDT409.Q27 -- B478 1999eb 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a967.731 aBesteman, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnraveling Somalia :bRace, Class, and the Legacy of Slavery /cCatherine Besteman. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b11 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Ethnography of Political Violence00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Somalia from the Margins: An Alternative Approach -- tChapter 2. Fieldwork, Surprises, and Historical Anthropology -- tChapter 3. Slavery and the Jubba Valley Frontier -- tChapter 4. The Settlement of the Upper Gosha, 1895-1988 -- tChapter 5. Hard Hair: Somali Constructions of Gosha Inferiority -- tChapter 6. Between Domination and Collusion: The Ambiguity of Gosha Life -- tChapter 7. Negotiating Hegemony and Producing Culture -- tChapter 8. The Political Economy of Subordination -- tChapter 9. Conclusion -- tEpilogue -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1991 the Somali state collapsed. Once heralded as the only true nation-state in Africa, the Somalia of the 1990s suffered brutal internecine warfare. At the same time a politically created famine caused the deaths of a half a million people and the flight of a million refugees. During the civil war, scholarly and popular analyses explained Somalia's disintegration as the result of ancestral hatreds played out in warfare between various clans and subclans. In Unraveling Somalia, Catherine Besteman challenges this view and argues that the actual pattern of violence—inflicted disproportionately on rural southerners—contradicts the prevailing model of ethnic homogeneity and clan opposition. She contends that the dissolution of the Somali nation-state can be understood only by recognizing that over the past century and a half there emerged in Somalia a social order based on principles other than simple clan organization—a social order deeply stratified on the basis of race, status, class, region, and language.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 4aAfrican Studies. 4aAfrican-American Studies. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aEuropean History. 4aFolklore. 4aHistory. 4aLinguistics. 4aMiddle Eastern Studies. 4aMiddle Eastern. 4aWorld History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229016540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812290165423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812290165.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041361-8  Penn Press eBook Package Social Sciences  a978-3-11-044252-6  Penn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK